                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="anglicism_sng_1" hclass="sense" fkcefr="c2"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">a word or phrase from the English language that is used in another language</span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">Anglicisms used in French include ‘le weekend’ and ‘un toast’.</span></li></ul><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/language?level=c2" title="Topic language"><span class="topic" href="l2:communication:language?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">Language</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="anglicism_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">mid 17th cent.: from Latin <span class="ei">Anglicus</span>, from <span class="ei">Angli</span> ‘the people of Angul’, a district of Schleswig (now in northern Germany), so named because of its shape; of Germanic origin, related to Old English <span class="ei">angul</span> + <span class="eb">-ism</span>.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
